1.body: Here's a breakdown of all of the parts of that command: build-lib: Wasm files are just a collection of exported memory and functions, so they're libraries! --export add: that's the function we want to be able to call from the web browser! in the next chapter, I'll show how to have zig do this for us so we don't have to list each one we want to export :) -dynamic: static libraries are known at compile time. Wasm libraries are dynamic, because you can't reach across library boundaries until runtime. This gives them lots of fun properties, like hot-swappability! -target wasm32-freestanding: good ole 32 bit web assembly, without any kind of operating system helpers, so "freestanding." Keepin' things lean and mean >:)

1.title: Huh?

10.body: Unfortunately, you can't just open that HTML file in your web browser. It needs to grab a file from your file system -- build/main.wasm -- and Chrome won't let it do that unless it's hosted from a web server. And, the static file servers you might typically use, like npx live-server or python3 -m http.server ... well, they actually treat Wasm files like random binaries, instead of marking them with the application/wasm MIME type, which means ... you can't load them :( Fortunately, there are still a couple static file servers I know of that correctly mark Wasm files. Try npx wasm-server and then go to localhost:3000/main.html
10.title: MIME woes

11.body: And lo and behold, if you look in your console ... the number 4 has been printed!
11.title: Hello, 4!

2.body: test % wc -c build/main.wasm 85 build/main.wasm As you can see, our Wasm file is only 85 bytes in size :O

2.title: Cute Lil Guy :>

3.body:
Great! Now let's try to use that Wasm file in our web browser. Fortunately, there's a handy function for that :) <!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en"> <head> <title>Useful C Wasm without Emscripten</title> <meta charset="UTF-8" /> <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width,initial-scale=1" /> <meta name="description" content="" /> </head> <body> <script> (async () => { const wasm = fetch("build/main.wasm"); const { instance } = await WebAssembly.instantiateStreaming(wasm, { env: {} }); console.log(instance.exports.add(2, 2)); })() </script> </body>
</html> Now your file system should look like this: test/ build/ main.wasm main.c main.html
